Rate Limiter – System Design Summary
1. Purpose

A rate limiter controls how many requests a client can make to a service within a defined time window. It protects downstream services from overload and ensures fair usage.

2. High-Level Approaches
a. Token Bucket (your chosen design)

A bucket holds tokens; each request consumes one.
Tokens are added at a fixed rate.
If the bucket is empty → request is rejected.

Why it’s preferred:
Smooth request distribution, handles bursts, predictable.

b. Leaky Bucket (for comparison)

Requests enter a queue and leak out at a fixed rate.
Good for producing a steady outgoing rate.

c. Fixed Window Counter

Simple but suffers boundary issues.

d. Sliding Window Log / Sliding Window Counter

More accurate; high memory cost depending on scale.

3. Your Design Using Token Bucket
Key Requirements

Support millions of client requests.

Rate limit per user or per IP.

Scalable horizontally.

Consistent throttling across multiple servers.

4. Components
a. API Gateway / Ingress

First point of contact.
Extracts client identifier (IP, API key, userID).

b. Distributed Cache (Redis)

Acts as the shared storage for token buckets.
Stores:

current token count

last refill timestamp

Redis operations must be atomic.

c. Limiter Service (Your core logic)

Implements:

calculate tokens to add since last request

cap tokens to maxBucketSize

check if token >= 1

update Redis

allow/deny request

send metrics/logs

You emphasized careful cleanup of expired entries to prevent unbounded growth.

5. Token Bucket Algorithm (Detailed)
On each request:

Read bucket from Redis.

Calculate elapsed_time = currentTime - lastRefillTime.

Compute tokens_to_add = elapsed_time * refillRate.

new_tokens = min(maxCapacity, old_tokens + tokens_to_add).

If new_tokens < 1: reject.

Else:

new_tokens -= 1

update Redis with new token count + lastRefillTime = now

Forward request.

Why this works:

No fixed window boundaries.
Natural smoothing of bursts.
Configurable capacity + refill rate.

6. Data Model in Redis

Key: rate_limit:{clientId}
Value:

{
  tokens: float,
  lastRefillTs: epoch_ms
}


Operations use Lua scripts or Redis transactions to ensure atomicity.

7. Cleanup Strategy

You proposed periodic cleanup to prevent unused buckets from living forever.

Approach:

Store TTL on Redis keys (slightly > refill window).

Redis auto-expires keys for inactive clients.

Optional background cleanup worker.

8. Scaling Strategy
a. Horizontal Scaling

All app servers query the same Redis cluster.
Consistency: Redis keeps token counters correct across nodes.

b. Sharding Redis

If scale increases, shard by clientId hash.

c. Multi-Region

Use region-local rate limiting to avoid cross-region latency.
If global limit is required:

Use CRDT counters (Redis Enterprise) or

Hierarchical limiting (global + local buckets).

9. Failure Scenarios
Redis down

Options:

Fail-open (let all traffic pass; risky)

Fail-closed (block all traffic; safe but harsh)

Hybrid based on endpoint criticality

Clock drift

Use server time, not client time.

Thundering herd

Use pipelining or Lua scripts for atomic operations.

10. Observability
Metrics

requests allowed/denied

Redis latency

bucket refill rate accuracy

per-user throttle %

Logs

throttle events

anomalies

latency spikes

Dashboards

Helps diagnose over-throttling or misconfigurations.

11. Example Config
maxTokens = 100
refillRate = 10 tokens/second
bucketTTL = 20 seconds

12. Strengths of Your Design

Burst handling with bounded max capacity

Accurate time-based refill

Atomic updates using Redis

Auto cleanup with TTL

Works with multiple web servers

Leverages existing cache infra (no heavy DB ops)
